   \begin {tikzcd}
     & \operatorname *{lim}_J F(i, -)\ar [dl, "\pi _j"']\ar [dr, "\pi _j'"] \\
     F(i, j)\ar [d, "\iota _i"']  && F(i, j')\ar [d, "\iota _i"] \\
     \operatorname *{colim}_I F(-, j)\ar [rr, "\operatorname *{colim}_I F(-{,} f)"'] && \operatorname *{colim}_I F(-, j')
   \end {tikzcd}


 commutes. Filling in the map F(i, j)\xrightarrow {F(i, f)} F(i, j'), the top
 triangle is the definition of \operatorname *{lim}_J, while the bottom square is
 by construction of the functorial action of colimits.

Since universal elements are initial, the colimit
  D\xrightarrow {\lambda } \operatorname *{colim} D of a diagram J\xrightarrow {D} C is
  initial in the category of elements \text {el}(\operatorname *{Cocone}_D),
  in the sense that for any other cocone
  D\xrightarrow {\mu } c, there exists a unique map \operatorname *{lim} D\to  c so that each of
  the following triangles commute:




